The directory is a set of reference material that helps reader find more information quickly. It contains the Glossary and the Reference Materials

Each of the views specified in Section Views provides a different perspective and design handle on a system, and each is valid and useful in its own right.
Although the views give different system perspectives, they are not independent. Elements of one view will be related to elements of other views, and we need to reason about these relations. For example, a module in a decomposition view may be manifested as one, part of one, or several components in one of the component-and-connector views, reflecting its runtime alter-ego. In general, mappings between views are many to many.
This section describes the relations that exist among the views.
As required by ANSI/IEEE 1471-2000, it also describes any known inconsistencies among the views.

When a software product line is being developed, this section details how the software covered by this AD is planned or expected to be reused in order to support the product line vision. In particular, this section includes a complete list of the variations that are planned to be produced and supported. The section may hyperlink to views as appropriate to provide further details of variations. "Variation" refers to a variant of the software produced through the use of pre-planned variation mechanisms made available in the software architecture. It may refer to a variant of one of the modules identified in this AD, or a collection of modules, or the entire system or subsystem covered by this AD. For each variation, the section identifies the increment(s) of the software build in which (a) the variation will be available; and (b) the variation will be used. Finally, this section describes any additional potential that exists to reuse one or more of the modules or their identified variations, even if this reuse is not currently planned for any increment.

The sub-parts of the section provide a description of why the architecture is the way that it is, and a convincing argument that the architecture is the right one to satisfy the behavioral and quality attribute goals levied upon it.

Interface Documentation Template 1. Interface Identity Elements have multiple interfaces or multiple elements may use an interface, in both these cases interfaces need names or identifiers. Some programming languages such as C#, Java or frameworks such as COM allow the interface names to be carried through in to the implementation. In certain cases naming the interface may not be sufficient and a version must be attached to understand interface evolution and have targeted dependencies. Typically naming the interface uniquely and including the interface version in the name are minimally sufficient. E.g. StreamReader2, StreamWriter1 etc. 2. Capabilities The heart of the interface is the set of capabilities provided to the actors. Capabilities could be typically operations e.g. software methods, procedures or functions but cold also include data streams, shared data, messages, force, electrical signals etc For each capability please add the information in the subsections. 2.1 Capability Syntax This is the capability’s signature. For software capabilities, this includes any information needed to write a syntactically correct program using the capability. The signature includes the name of the capability, names and data types of the arguments if any and structure and data type of the return values if any. <TBD SysML References to non software interfaces> 2.2 Capability Semantics This describes the result of using the capability. It speaks to what the capability does from the perspective of the actor using it. This could be:
  • Assignment of values to the parameters and the returned values including their purpose an semantics. The value set could be simple as setting the value of a return argument or persistent e.g. to a file or a database.
  • Changes to the elements externally visible state caused by invoking the capability. E.g. initialization, connection, allocation, deallocation etc.
  • Events signaled or messages sent.
  • Side effects on other environmental elements e.g. if a capability to destroy an object is invoked, the object access can result in errors in the future.
  • Humanly observable results e.g. pressing a switch causing a light to turn on.
  • Whether or not the execution of the capability will be atomic or may be suspended or interrupted. If it is synchronous or asynchronous.
  • Usage restrictions. The circumstances under which the capability can be used. There may be data that needs initializing or operations need to be invoked in a certain order. There could authorization restrictions e.g. certain operations can only be performed by authorized users. There may be limits on simultaneous access e.g. capabilities that change the internal state of the element can only be invoked by a single actor at a time and concurrent access may result in errors or other protocols such as serialization.
Semantic information may be convened as a set of pre-conditions and post-conditions written in plain text or in Boolean algebra expressions. More complex semantics may be conveyed through UML behavior diagrams such as state charts. 2.3 Capability Error Handling The errors conditions and exceptions that can be raised by the resource. 3 Data Types and Constants This refers to new types of data that need to be created (structs, classes, unions, enumerations) for input parameters or return values. Capabilities also may require new constants to be created e.g. for default values. The new types would be created in Enterprise Architect and referred here. 4 Error Handling If all or many the capabilities in the interface exhibit common error handling behavior, the pattern may be specified once here for brevity. Per capability error handling may override common behavior specified here. 5. Variability This specifies if the interface allows the element to be configured in a certain fashion. For each configuration parameter specify the following 5.1. Configuration Parameter Name 5.2 Configuration Parameter Type and Value Range 5.3 Configuration Value Bind Time This is relevant when configuration may be set synchronous but picked up delayed due to caching or graceful pre-processing to finish the semantic effects of previous value etc. e.g. a timer interval may only be effective if the event is not being triggered or processed. 5.4 Configuration Value Semantic Effect Focus on the less obvious such as a cache flush that may occur if a cache size is changed via reconfiguration etc. 6. Quality Attribute Characteristics This contains the quality attribute characteristics such as performance or reliability the interface promises to the element’s users. This will translate to constraints on the elements that implement the interface. If the interface is provided to external element as a part of a service in a service-oriented architecture, the QA characteristics form portions of the service level agreement (SLA). This will include and not be restricted to response time, availability level, capacity in terms of concurrent requests etc. 7. Rationale and Design Issues This specifies the motivation behind the interface design, constraints and compromises, alternative designs considered and rejected and any insight regarding how to change the interface in the future. 8 Usage Guide Sometimes the interface as a capability set may impose patterns and constraints on how the capabilities are used in conjunction of each other and other environmental elements. Typical order of invocation e.g. initialize, validate and use is specified here. UML behavior diagrams such as sequence diagrams in Enterprise Architect are a good way of specifying usage.

Variability Guide Variation points are places in the architecture where specific instances of flexibility are built in. The variability guide describes how to exercise the variation points shown in the view. The variety of variation points and how to document them is explained in detail in the Architecture Document Guide. For each variation point the following information is required. 1. Description 2. Available options and their effects 3. Conditions of applicability 4. Binding time of the option 5. How is the option exercised? 5. Interdependencies among variation points
  • Element substitution: The UML relation <realizes> is a good way to depict that an interface can be realized by different implementations. This variation point can be documented using a dedicated UML diagram in Enterprise Architect that uses the realizes relationship.
  • Component Replication: Creating multiple instances of a component to provide greater capability e.g. scaling services by deploying multiple instances on the same machine or different machines.
Each variation point may be represented by a separate diagram that contain primarily textual elements to represent information. Variation option exercise such as template substitution, method invocation etc may be represented using appropriate UML diagrams to augment this information.

Context Diagram A context diagram shows how the system or portion of the system depicted in the view relates to its environment. This is useful in certain kind of views such as 1. Component and Connector Views i.e. How UML components depicted in the view relate to other components in a larger system. 2. Data Model View 3. Deployment View 4. Installation View etc.

This Element Interface Template describes what is contained in a typical element interface. Some of this information can be directly entered in to the element body of the EA element (UML or otherwise) Some interface information may need element specific diagrams with textual information for complex elements.
This diagram will not be present in the actual documentation. Rather each of the views part of the actual documentation will contain relevant information per this template.

Primary Presentation The primary presentation shows the elements and relations of the view. It includes the primary elements and relations and but may not include all of them. E.g. error handling or exception processing may be relegated to supporting documentation. In the case of most view types e.g. module, component and connector or allocation, the primary presentation will be graphical. This will consist of one or more diagrams created in Enterprise Architect. If the architecture being described is of a simple system such as a service, a single diagram will suffice. If the architecture consists of a system containing distinct important subsystems e.g. service encapsulating a hardware/ firmware subsystem, refined diagrams for each relevant subsystem will be included in the primary presentation.

Element Catalog The element catalog contains the at least those elements depicted in the primary presentation. The element catalog is comprehensive and should also include additional elements, omitted from the primary presentation for clarity. Enterprise Architect will serve as the primary repository of architectural information and element catalog for any view should be generated from Enterprise Architect. Any diagram in Enterprise Architect will contain elements which are automatically added to a package and become a part of the element catalog. If the primary presentation does not include every element, then in the interest of conciseness, the element catalog may be represented as a link to an EA diagram that contains every element in the view. EA will allow further drill down per element regarding its role, purpose etc. The Element Catalog has the following information about Elements Elements and their properties This section names each element in the view and lists the properties of that element. The specific properties for elements are dependent on view styles. E.g. elements in a decomposition view may have a “responsibility” property etc Relations and their properties Each view has specific relation types that it depicts among elements in the view. Mostly the relations are visible in the primary presentation. However, some relations may be omitted from the primary presentation for brevity and clarity. Those would be recorded in greater detail here. As with the Element catalog, detailed relations can be shown as links to specific diagrams in Enterprise Architect that show the relationship between the elements. If the primary presentation covers this information, the section will be empty(but not deleted to ensure availability for future use). Element Interfaces This section documents element interfaces. Please refer to the Interface Documentation Template for details regarding interface documentation Element Behavior Some elements may have complex interactions with their environment e.g. thread model, internal state changes etc. These would be recorded here. Behavior can be documented using a combination of UML Use Cases, Sequence Diagrams, Communication Diagrams, Activity Diagrams and State Machine Diagrams. These diagrams will be created in Enterprise Architect and referenced here.

This Module View Information Template describes what is contained in a typical module view. This diagram will not be present in the actual documentation. Rather each of the views part of the actual documentation will contain relevant information per this template.

A module refers to a unit of implementation. Although typically associated with source code, information models, xml files, config files and other artifacts are modules as well. A module suggests implementation units and artifacts with less emphasis on delivery medium and what goes on at runtime. A library or binary containing the business logic of an application or a service is an example of a module. A module is characterized by enumerating its set of responsibilities which are foremost among the module’s properties. Module views consist of modules which are related through relationships such as is part of, is a, depends on etc. Typical purposes for module views are
  • Provide a blueprint for code construction. Modules and physical structures such as source code files share a close relationship.
  • Facilitate impact analysis. Module views show dependencies between modules helping trace cascades of design and test changes.
  • Plan incremental development.
  • Support requirements traceability analysis. Modules partition the system. Module responsibilities can be mapped to specific requirements. In the case, where a sequence of module invocations is needed for meeting a functional requirement, the documented sequence may be mapped to the requirement.
  • Explain the functionality of the system and structure of the code base.
  • Support definition of work assignments, implementation schedules and budget information.
  • Show the structure of information to be persisted.

The Module View in the Architectural Document shows modules using UML Structural Diagrams such as Package Diagram, Class Diagram etc. The module view may include a presentation that has a layered style to represent the relationship such as usage or dependency between various layers represented as packages. It also may include a class diagram with various relationship such as generalization, specialization, template substitution, usage, composition etc. Depending on the complexity of relationships, separate diagrams may be created that show a subset of relationships. e.g. Generalization, Specialization and Template specialization focused diagram or Usage and Dependency focused diagram. The Elements that appear in these diagram contain as a part of their properties in Enterprise architect, the element properties.

This Implementation View Information Template describes what is contained in a typical implementation view. This diagram will not be present in the actual documentation. Rather each of the views part of the actual documentation will contain relevant information per this template.

The data model describes the static information structure in terms of data entities and their relationships. It is often represented graphically in entity relationship diagrams or UML class diagrams. The elements are data entities for storage and representation of information. These entities data attributes along with typical metadata such as name, type, id, data access rules etc. The relationships expressed in the data model are between these data entities such as one-to-one, one-to-many, many-to-many, generalization /specialization and aggregation. A simple data model may involve an entity relationship diagram between various data elements. The data model may consist of multiple views indicating varying refinement e.g.
  • Conceptual: The conceptual data model focuses on entities and their relationships as perceived in the problem domain. Typically Entity Relationship diagrams can be used to represent this.
  • Logical: The logical data model is a refinement/evolution of the conceptual data model towards a data management technology such as relational databases. Details regarding relationships start to appear.
  • Physical: The physical data model is concerned with the implementation data entities. It contains optimizations for merging or partitioning entities, duplicating data and creation of identification keys and indexes.
In addition this view may also contain Data Flow Diagrams representing the flow of the data elements through various components.

This Component and Connectors, and Interactions and Behaviors View Information Template describes what is contained in a typical CnC view. This diagram will not be present in the actual documentation. Rather each of the views part of the actual documentation will contain relevant information per this template.

The information in this view is typically focused on the runtime behavior of the product or system. Typically a UML Component diagram represents the interactions between the components that make up the system and serves the primary presentation of the view. The Connectors in the CnC view may be direct UML connectors or if complex may be represented as UML Components themselves. All elements (components and connector) in the view would have a name and a type. In addition, there may be type specific properties, to guide the implementation and configuration of the elements with specified values for properties such as quality attributes. Typical properties are
  • Reliability: Likelihood of failure for a given component or connector.
  • Performance: Response time provided by the component under certain loads. Latencies and throughput expectations of a given connector.
  • Resource requirements: Processing and storage needs for both components and connectors.
  • Functionality: Functions performed by the element
  • Security: Security features enforced or provided such as encryption, audit trails or authentication
  • Concurrency: Does the component execute as a separate process or thread?
  • Tier: For a tiered topology what tier the component resides in.
Ports and roles may also have properties associated with them such as maximum sustainable request rate may be specified and associated with a particular server port. In addition various behavior diagrams such as 1. UML Sequence Diagrams. 2. UML Activity Diagrams 3. UML State Machine diagrams 4. UML Timing Diagrams may be utilized as additional presentations to convey runtime behavior.

This Implementation View Information Template describes what is contained in a typical implementation view. This diagram will not be present in the actual documentation. Rather each of the views part of the actual documentation will contain relevant information per this template.

The implementation style maps modules from the module style to the files, folders and source repository locations for the source code and tests. A primary presentation diagram would suffice. This style of view is important for subsequent maintenance of products with a multi-year life time.

This Install View Information Template describes what is contained in a typical install view. This diagram will not be present in the actual documentation. Rather each of the views part of the actual documentation will contain relevant information per this template.

The install style of view allocates components of a component and connector style view to a file management system in the production environment. It is meant to describe the production destination of various build artifacts such as binaries, libraries, configuration files, version files, resources (images, text), manifests etc. The UML stereotype <<artifact>> is typically used to denote elements in this view. The containment relationship between artifacts is shown using the <<manifest> relationship. Due to the compact nature of the information conveyed here, install style views are typically sufficiently described by their primary presentation alone.

This Deployment View Information Template describes what is contained in a typical deployment view. This diagram will not be present in the actual documentation. Rather each of the views part of the actual documentation will contain relevant information per this template.

Deployment style views allocate or map execution elements from the Component and Connector views such as software applications, processes etc. to the hardware resources for execution. The logic elements are typically shared from or linked from the relevant Component and Connector view. The environment or hardware elements defined in this view carry properties such as processor speed, memory and disk size, network bandwidth etc. The most typical relationship in a deployment view is represented as <<deploy>> in UML. Additional relationships could be
  • Migrates-to: This maps a software element on one processor to the same software element on another processor, where the software element may move between processors but only exists on one at a time. This is useful in a regular deployment for a hardware switch where the software element is transferred to the new hardware.
  • Copy-migrates-to: Here a copy of the software element can be on the new processor while retaining the original. This is a typical scaling scenario where additional hardware is deployed while retaining existing one.
  • Execution-migrates-to: Here the software code residency is retained on both the old and the new processor, however there may be only one executing process on a single hardware processor while the other processors can retain the code to execute in stand by if needed. This is a typical blue-green deployment scenario.
Environment or Hardware elements typically would have the following properties
  • CPU properties: instruction execution speed, number of processors, memory capacity, bus speed, cache size etc.
  • Memory properties: Size and speed of various memory stores.
  • Disk and other storage capacity
  • Bandwidth of communication channels
  • Fault tolerance: If multiple hardware units perform the same function, the failover control mechanism needs to be associated with them.
The software elements in the context of this view carry the following additional properties
  • Resource consumption: The average CPU or memory requirements for a particular component to run.
  • Resource constraints: Various budgets e.g. a latency budget for a particular action to execute.
  • Safety criticality: Information about whether a component must always run and consequences of failure.
  • Migration trigger: The logical trigger that needs to occur for the software element to move from one hardware to another.
Deployment style views describe aspects of the architecture that are required for performance and security analysis.

The physical data store view maps elements from the data model view to various physical data locations such as databases, cloud stores etc.
Candidate diagrams for details include. 1. UML deployment diagrams. 2. Data Modelling diagrams in Extended that contain elements for physical database representation. 3. Specific AWS or Google Cloud related diagrams.

This Physical Data Store View Information Template describes what is contained in a typical physical data store view. This diagram will not be present in the actual documentation. Rather each of the views part of the actual documentation will contain relevant information per this template.

The work assignment style of view maps modules in the module style views to the teams or individuals who would work on them. The environment element are persons, teams, departments, subcontractors etc. The allocated-to relationship is used to map the two. The environment element properties may be augmented team sizes, estimates, geographical constraints etc. The work assignment style of view could be dynamic if there is a lot of team churn. However, resource and team allocations do have a material impact on the decomposition of an architecture. Quality attributes of modules then can be written in to contracts with external companies.
There are no specific UML diagrams specifically associated with the work assignment view. However, a simple mapping table can serve as the primary presentation with information regarding the environmental elements in the element catalog.
A BIZBOK Organization Map Diagram may be used to represent various organizational elements and map them to various elements from a responsibility perspective.
